<subSubSection lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="224" pageId="18" pageNumber="223" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="18.[683,1199,582,1730]" box="[683,951,880,906]" pageId="18" pageNumber="223">
<emphasis box="[683,951,880,906]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="223">Descriptive characters</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[683,1199,582,1730]" pageId="18" pageNumber="223">
This is a medium-sized pipistrelle with a forearm length of 
<quantity box="[918,1090,949,975]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" metricValueMax="3.44" metricValueMin="3.16" pageId="18" pageNumber="223" unit="mm" value="33.0" valueMax="34.4" valueMin="31.6">31.6–34.4 mm</quantity>
in specimens referred to this species from 
<collectingCountry box="[1084,1198,984,1010]" name="Myanmar" pageId="18" pageNumber="223">Myanmar</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[732,792,1017,1043]" name="India" pageId="18" pageNumber="223">India</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="DAS, P. K. &amp; Y. P. SINHA" box="[836,1091,1017,1044]" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society" pageId="18" pageNumber="223" pagination="252 - 254" part="92" refId="ref21463" refString="DAS, P. K., and Y. P. SINHA. 1995. Occurrence of the Japanese pipistrelle, Pipistrellus abramus (Tem- minck, 1840) (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) in Myanmar (Burma) and India. Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society, 92: 252 - 254." title="Occurrence of the Japanese pipistrelle, Pipistrellus abramus (Tem- minck, 1840) (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) in Myanmar (Burma) and India" type="journal article" year="1995">Das and Sinha (1995)</bibRefCitation>
and 29.1 and 
<quantity box="[734,840,1052,1078]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.06" pageId="18" pageNumber="223" unit="mm" value="30.6">30.6 mm</quantity>
in two extralimital specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[751,850,1086,1112]" name="Vietnam" pageId="18" pageNumber="223">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
(
<tableCitation box="[869,963,1086,1112]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="7.[130,143,167,188]" captionTargetId="graphics@7.[127,1200,376,1322]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 4. External and bacular measurements (in mm) and body mass (in g) of 21 species of Vespertilionidae recorded from Myanmar, including the lengths of head and body (HB), tail (TAIL), foot (HF), tibia (TIBIA), forearm (FA), fifth, fourth, third metacarpal (5MET, 4MET and 3MET), ear (E), and baculum (BAC LGT). Sample sizes for males and females differing from those reported under n are given in parentheses after the measurement. Mean and SD are included when sample size is 3 or more. Data in italics are based on specimens collected outside Myanmar. Species listed in order of genera, and taxonomic groups and subgroups based on Corbet and Hill (1992) and Bates and Harrison (1997)" pageId="18" pageNumber="223">Table 4</tableCitation>
) (no local material was seen by the current authors: FA = 
<quantity box="[683,854,1155,1181]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1049999999999995" metricValueMax="3.12" metricValueMin="3.09" pageId="18" pageNumber="223" unit="mm" value="31.049999999999997" valueMax="31.2" valueMin="30.9">30.9–31.2 mm</quantity>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="HENDRICHSEN, D. K. &amp; P. J. J. BATES &amp; B. D. HAYES &amp; J. L. WALSTON" box="[892,1185,1155,1181]" journalOrPublisher="Myotis" pageId="18" pageNumber="223" pagination="35 - 122" part="39" refId="ref21801" refString="HENDRICHSEN, D. K., P. J. J. BATES, B. D. HAYES, and J. L. WALSTON. 2001. Recent records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Vietnam with six species new to the country. Myotis, 39: 35 - 122." title="Recent records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Vietnam with six species new to the country" type="journal article" year="2001">
Hendrichsen 
<emphasis box="[1048,1107,1155,1181]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="223">et al.</emphasis>
, 2001
</bibRefCitation>
). It has a very long penis (
<bibRefCitation author="BATES, P. J. J. &amp; D. L. HARRISON" bookContentInfo="258 pp." box="[974,1185,1189,1216]" journalOrPublisher="Harrison Zoological Museum Publications, Sevenoaks" pageId="18" pageNumber="223" refId="ref20800" refString="BATES, P. J. J., and D. L. HARRISON. 1997. The bats of the Indian Subcontinent. Harrison Zoological Museum Publications, Sevenoaks, 258 pp." title="The bats of the Indian Subcontinent" type="book" year="1997">
Bates 
<emphasis box="[1048,1107,1189,1215]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="223">et al.</emphasis>
, 1997
</bibRefCitation>
). The dorsal pelage is grey-brown with dark hair roots. The ventral surface has pale buffy-grey hair tips and dark roots. The fifth metacarpal is about equal in length to the third and fourth. The baculum, which is long, 8.9–12.0 mm in extralimital specimens, is thin and sinuous with a characteristic double curve when viewed laterally (Fig. 2C). The base is slightly bilobate and the tip has an indication towards being bifid (
<bibRefCitation author="BATES, P. J. J. &amp; D. L. HARRISON" bookContentInfo="258 pp." journalOrPublisher="Harrison Zoological Museum Publications, Sevenoaks" pageId="18" pageNumber="223" refId="ref20800" refString="BATES, P. J. J., and D. L. HARRISON. 1997. The bats of the Indian Subcontinent. Harrison Zoological Museum Publications, Sevenoaks, 258 pp." title="The bats of the Indian Subcontinent" type="book" year="1997">
Bates 
<emphasis box="[683,746,1566,1592]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="223">et al.</emphasis>
, 1997
</bibRefCitation>
). The skull has thin zygomata without processes. The second incisor (I3) exceeds the height of the secondary cusp of the first incisor (I2) and is about equal in crown area. The upper canine (C1) has
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[130,646,163,1115]" pageId="19" pageNumber="224">a secondary cusp. The first upper premolar (P2) is about equal in crown area to I2 and is intruded from the toothrow. The first lower premolar (P2) is about two-thirds to three- quarters the crown area of the second (P4).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="224" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="19.[130,646,163,1115]" box="[130,309,369,395]" pageId="19" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis box="[130,309,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="224">Similar species</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[130,646,163,1115]" pageId="19" pageNumber="224">
The skull of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Temminck" authorityYear="1840" box="[330,465,403,429]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Vespertilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="224" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="abramus">
<emphasis box="[330,465,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="224">P. abramus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cannot be dis- tinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="in Lindsay" authorityYear="1926" box="[339,519,438,464]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Pipistrellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="224" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="coromandra">
<emphasis box="[339,519,438,464]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="224">P. coromandra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by either size or morphology. However, the penis and baculum of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Temminck" authorityYear="1840" box="[269,400,506,532]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Vespertilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="224" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="abramus">
<emphasis box="[269,400,506,532]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="224">P. abramus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
greatly exceed those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="in Lindsay" authorityYear="1926" box="[164,338,541,567]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Pipistrellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="224" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="coromandra">
<emphasis box="[164,338,541,567]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="224">P. coromandra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in length. The shape, but not the length of the baculum, appears to be the only reliable character to distinguish be- tween 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Temminck" authorityYear="1840" box="[208,341,643,669]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Vespertilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="224" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="abramus">
<emphasis box="[208,341,643,669]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="224">P. abramus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[399,559,643,669]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="224">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1915" box="[399,555,643,669]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Pipistrellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="224" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="paterculus">P. paterculus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="224" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="19.[130,646,163,1115]" box="[130,226,712,738]" pageId="19" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis box="[130,226,712,738]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="224">Ecology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[130,646,163,1115]" pageId="19" pageNumber="224">
Nothing is known of the ecology of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Temminck" authorityYear="1840" box="[130,266,781,807]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Vespertilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="224" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="abramus">
<emphasis box="[130,266,781,807]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="224">P. abramus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[312,426,781,807]" name="Myanmar" pageId="19" pageNumber="224">Myanmar</collectingCountry>
. The only known specimen was collected on 25 November, 1926 at Namkam (
<bibRefCitation author="DAS, P. K. &amp; Y. P. SINHA" box="[366,632,849,876]" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society" pageId="19" pageNumber="224" pagination="252 - 254" part="92" refId="ref21463" refString="DAS, P. K., and Y. P. SINHA. 1995. Occurrence of the Japanese pipistrelle, Pipistrellus abramus (Tem- minck, 1840) (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) in Myanmar (Burma) and India. Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society, 92: 252 - 254." title="Occurrence of the Japanese pipistrelle, Pipistrellus abramus (Tem- minck, 1840) (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) in Myanmar (Burma) and India" type="journal article" year="1995">Das and Sinha, 1995</bibRefCitation>
). This area is currently characterised by for- ested hills, with bamboo in the more dis- turbed areas and agricultural land, primarily rice paddy, in the Lengchuan Jiang (River) valley (data from the 
<collectingRegion box="[438,531,1021,1047]" country="Myanmar" name="Yangon" pageId="19" pageNumber="224">Yangon</collectingRegion>
Univer- sity/Harrison Institute expedition to the area in March, 2002).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
